---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import solarPanelLogo from "../assets/solar-panel-logo.png";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "@fontsource-variable/lexend";
---

<Layout>
    <nav class="mx-12 my-4">
        <header class="flex justify-end gap-8 uppercase font-light">
            <a href="/team">Team</a>
            <a href="https://github.com/alvgaona/vxc">GitHub</a>
        </header>
    </nav>
    <div class="flex justify-center my-12">
        <main class="mx-64 px-24">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-6">
                <div class="flex flex-col items-center gap-2">
                    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4">
                        <Image class="self-center" src={solarPanelLogo} alt="A solar panel" height="100" />
                        <h1 class="font-light text-4xl">Solar Panel Hot Spots Detection Techniques</h1>
                    </div>
                    <h2 class="font-extralight text-sm">
                        A computer vision project at Universidad Politécnica de Madrid
                    </h2>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <div class="flex justify-between font-extralight pb-2">
                        <span>Computer Vision</span>
                        <span>January 1, 2026</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 border-t-[0.5px] pt-4">
                        <div class="flex flex-col self-center font-extralight text-sm justify-center items-center">
                            <div class="flex gap-4">
                                <span>Alvaro J. Gaona</span>
                                <span>Lucas Gomez Velayos</span>
                                <span>Pedro Alvarez Monteagudo</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="flex gap-4">
                                <span>José D. Valda Peñaranda</span>
                                <span>Peter A. Pasuy Quevedo</span>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <h2 class="font-light text-xl text-spectral-blue">Abstract</h2>
                        <p class="text-md font-light text-justify">
                            Thermal hotspots in photovoltaic modules are a leading cause of performance loss,
                            accelerated degradation, and safety concerns, making timely and scalable detection essential
                            for modern solar farm operations. This article presents a hybrid approach that combines
                            classical computer vision with deep learning to analyze radiometric thermal imagery,
                            demonstrating that complementary methods can be orchestrated to balance interpretability,
                            robustness, and speed. The proposed workflow emphasizes rapid prototyping and modularity,
                            enabling practitioners to assemble a practical end-to-end pipeline—from data capture and
                            preprocessing through candidate generation, classification, and reporting—using readily
                            available tools and modest datasets. Designed for integration with existing monitoring
                            systems, the workflow outputs per-module alerts, normalized severity indicators, and
                            artifacts suitable for operations and maintenance decision-making at scale. Empirical
                            results show that the combined strategy improves detection reliability over single-family
                            methods while preserving transparency in how anomalies are identified, supporting both quick
                            pilots and production-ready deployments across handheld, drone, and fixed installations.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </main>
    </div>
</Layout>
